Source <- ESCardio guidelines

  • If patient presents to PCI center, aim for wire crossing time of < 60 minutes.
  • If the patientpresents to a Non PCI Center:
    • Is it possible to do PCI within 120 minutes of presentation? If yes
      • Then transfer to PCI capable center with an aim of wire crossing at < 90 minutes.
    • If it is not possible do to PCI within 120 minutes, go for fibrinolysis.
  • Target door to balloon time for STEMI PCI 90 minutes. (lowered from previous recommendation of 120 minutes).
    • Target door to needle time should be < 30 minutes**.< 10 minutes**!

[!INFO] Key points

  1. Patients with suspected NSTEMI should have hs-troponins taken at 0 hrs, 1hr and 2hrs to check for progressive rise in troponin. (i.e takeaway: it's never "too soon to take the first troponin level")

Heparin:

  • UHF is given because it's needed to ⭐prevent intraarterial thrombus formation during the PCI and also (poor evidence) to prevent the coronary thrombus propagation.
    • Obviously, this pre-procedure anticoagulation is given irrespective of whether the patient has a STEMI or NSTEMI.
  • Anticoagulation is not needed after the procedure. Source

Anti-platelet treatment in post-acute STEMI management

  1. Twelve Month DAPT remains the default for STEMI patients.
    1. Preferred drugs for this are prasugrel and ticagrelor.
  2. In High bleeding risk patients, abbreviated DAPT strategies or DAPT deescalation strageties can be used.
    1. De-escalation means switching from prasugrel / ticagrelor to clopidogrel.

[!INFO] Contrast with NSEMI management:
NSTEMI also requires PCI but at different time cut-offs.

  1. Immediate if :
  • If patient is haemodyamically unstable, has life threatening arrhythmias, heart failure etc.
  1. Early (within 24 hours) if any one of :
  • Diagnosis of NSTEMI is confirmed
  • Dynamic ST segment changes are preesent.
  • GRACE risk > 140
  1. Selective or non-invasive
  • If the patient doesn't fall into the categories above.
    Followed by DAPT for 12 months.

[!NOTE] ROME IV (search ROME 4) criteria
2. Altered stool consistency

- Also, **arthritis**, #lymphadenopathy , **sore throat** and #splenomegaly
  • AOST shows a dramatic response to NSAIDS.

[!INFO] Dopamine treatment is delayed until motor symptoms become troublesome.
According to the algorithm here and several others, dopamine treatment is not started as soon as symptoms appear. Early treatment is with MAOB-Is or anticholinergics for younger patients.
